{"id":"2002.00605","submitter":"Yuehua Su","authors":"Yuehua Su and Chao Zhang","title":"Coincidence angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy: Proposal for\n  detection of two-particle correlations","comments":"14 pages, 5 figures; Revised version for publication with typo\n  corrections upon V3","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 101, 205110 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.101.205110","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) is one powerful\nexperimental technique to study the electronic structure of materials. As many\nelectron materials show unusual many-body correlations, the technique to detect\ndirectly these many-body correlations will play important roles in the study of\ntheir many-body physics. In this article, we propose a technique to detect\ndirectly the two-particle correlations, a coincidence ARPES (cARPES) where two\nincident photons excite two respective photoelectrons which are detected in\ncoincidence. While the one-photon-absorption and one-photoelectron-emission\nARPES provides the single-particle spectrum function, the proposed cARPES with\ntwo-photon absorption and two-photoelectron emission is relevant to a\ntwo-particle Bethe-Salpeter wave function. Examples of the coincidence\ndetection probability of the cARPES for a free Fermi gas and a\nBardeen-Cooper-Schrieffer (BCS) superconducting state are studied in detail. We\nalso propose another two experimental techniques, a coincidence angle-resolved\nphotoemission and inverse-photoemission spectroscopy (cARP/IPES) and a\ncoincidence angle-resolved inverse-photoemission spectroscopy (cARIPES). As all\nof these proposed coincidence techniques can provide the two-particle frequency\nBethe-Salpeter wave functions, they can show the momentum and energy dependent\ntwo-particle dynamical physics of the material electrons in the\nparticle-particle or particle-hole channel. Thus, they can be introduced to\nstudy the Cooper-pair physics in the superconductor, the itinerant magnetism in\nthe metallic ferromagnet/antiferromagnet, and the particle-hole pair physics in\nthe metallic nematic state. Moreover, as the two-particle Bethe-Salpeter wave\nfunctions also involve the inner-pair dynamical physics, these proposed\ncoincidence techniques can be used to study the inner-pair time-retarded\nphysics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Feb 2020 08:59:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 23 Feb 2020 17:30:37 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 27 Feb 2020 02:20:06 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 8 May 2020 12:09:56 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 11 May 2020 12:04:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-05-12"}
